article.description: Betty Lennox had a triumphant debut, scoring 15 points and making four clutch free throws in the final seconds, as the resurgent Miami Sol held off the Orlando Miracle, 69-65.
article.headline: Sol righting ship at Miracle's expense
article.linkText: Miami wins second straight after 0-5 start
article.story:
ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Sheri Sam and Betty Lennox combined for 32
points as the Miami Sol outlasted the Orlando Miracle 69-65 on Saturday night.

	   The win was the second straight for Miami after starting the
season with five straight losses. Orlando lost for the second
straight game.

	   Shannon Johnson had a chance to tie the game for the Miracle
(3-3) when she went to the line for three free throws with 10.8
seconds to play and Orlando trailing 67-64.

	   Johnson missed the first two free throws before making the last
one. She finished the game with 15 points, three rebounds and three
assists.

	   Sam had 17 points, Lennox had 15 and Pollyanna Johns-Kimbrough
added 13 points for the Sol (2-5). Katie Douglas had 10 points for
Orlando.

	   Lennox was playing in her first game for the Sol after being
acquired in a trade with Minnesota June 11. The 5-8 guard made four
free throws and grabbed a rebound in the final 45 seconds of the
game.

	   "I'm not really sure what my role with this team is going to
be,'' Lennox said. "I just wanted to come out here and score some
points and learn this offense.

	   "I'm a veteran player, I'll give this team something they're
looking for.''

	   Each team had 18 turnovers in the game. Miami had 17 turnovers
in the second half.

	   "Someday we're going to play with discipline and not commit so
many turnovers,'' Miracle coach Dee Brown said. "I keep waiting
for that to happen.''

	   After falling behind 52-40 with 9:38 to play, Orlando went on a
13-4 run to pull within three, 56-53, with 4:11 to play. Miami
outscored the Miracle 8-2 at the start of the second half to take a
37-29 lead with 17:31 to play.

	   Earlier Saturday, the Sol activated center Ruth Riley from the
injured list. Riley broke the pinky finger on her right hand May 26
and had not played a game for the Sol this season. The second year
player from Notre Dame played in a splint and shot left-handed
throughout the game, including free throws.

	   "They have heart down there in Miami,'' Brown said. "Ruth
Riley played with one hand. We had chances, but had too many mental
breakdowns in the final three or four minutes.''
